note_ID: NA
title:
Independent and combined effects of daytime heat stress
and night-time recovery determine thermal performance
citation: Bai, Chun-Ming, Gang Ma, Wan-Zhi Cai, and Chun-Sen Ma. "Independent and combined effects of daytime heat stress and night-time recovery determine thermal performance." Biology open 8, no. 3 (2019).
notes_moderators: Endpoint was loss of locomotion and "started to twitch". Heating rate was changed between 25 to 31C (i.e. 0.25C/min) and 31C to 42C (i.e. 0.1C/min). We took 0.1C/min as the ramping rate because all animals reached CTmax at temperatures higher than 31C.  Acclimation treatments were variable (e.g. 28C during the day, 15C during the night) but comparable between treatments. Here, we compared the treatments 28-15 and 35-15. Mean humidity was taken.
notes_es: Data extracted from the raw data

minor_concerns: Treatments were acclimated for different durations.

title: Effects of acclimation temperature on the thermal physiology in two geographically distinct populations of lake sturgeon (Acipenser fulvescens)
citation: Bugg, William S., Gwangseok R. Yoon, Alexandra N. Schoen, Andrew Laluk, Catherine Brandt, W. Gary Anderson, and Ken M. Jeffries. "Effects of acclimation temperature on the thermal physiology in two geographically distinct populations of lake sturgeon (Acipenser fulvescens)." Conservation Physiology 8, no. 1 (2020): coaa087.
minor_concerns: Treatments were acclimated for different durations.
notes_moderators: Data from the "Winnipeg" population. Elevation was estimated using Google Earth. "season" was taken as "spring" because animals were collected in May and June. Mean body mass between acclimation treatments (table 2) was calculated. Age was the age at the beginning of the acclimation (30 dph) + 30 days of acclimation. Animals acclimated to 16C were acclimated for longer than animals acclimated to 20C. The acc_duration was taken as 30 days (the acc_duration of the 20C acclimated treatment).
notes_es: Data digitised from figure. Sample size was the number of data points in the figure

title: Costs and benefits of thermal acclimation for codling moth, Cydia pomonella (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae): implications for pest control and the sterile insect release programme
citation: Chidawanyika, Frank, and John S. Terblanche. "Costs and benefits of thermal acclimation for codling moth, Cydia pomonella (Lepidoptera: Tortricidae): implications for pest control and the sterile insect release programme." Evolutionary Applications 4, no. 4 (2011): 534-544.
minor_concerns: Treatments were acclimated for different durations. SD possibly underestimated.
notes_moderators: The year taken was the year at which the colony culture was first established. Animals that developed at 25C were acclimated for slightly longer (24-48h more) than animals acclimated at the other temperature because all animals were brought to 25C upon eclosion. The time at common temperature and age were taken as 1.5 days because animals were tested at 24-48h post eclosion. CTmax endpoint was "loss of coordinated motor function", which is similar to the loss of righting response.
notes_es: Data digitisted from figure. It was not indicated whether the error provided in the figure was the SD, SE or CI. We assumed it was SD as it is the most likely error type given the significance level (if it was SE, confidence intervals would most likely overlap)

title: Ontogenetic change in the temperature tolerance of larval Bufo marinus (Anura: Bufonidae)
journal: Comparative Biochemistry and Physiology Part A
citation: Floyd, Robert B. "Ontogenetic change in the temperature tolerance of larval Bufo marinus (Anura: Bufonidae)." Comparative Biochemistry and Physiology Part A: Physiology 75, no. 2 (1983): 267-271.
minor_concerns: Treatments were acclimated for different durations.
notes_moderators: Data for animals at the Gosner stage 20. Bufo marinus was changed to "Rhinella marina" because the species name changed. The species was considered "aquatic" because they manipulated the water temperature. Geographical coordinates were not taken because the location was approximate ("campus of Griffith University, Brisbane, Australia"). Griffith University has now expanded greatly. Season was taken to be "summer" as animals were collected in February in Australia. "mobility" was taken as "mobile" because the incubation spanned both immobile and mobile life stages. All embryos developed at 30C and were then allocated to different treatments, meaning that animals acclimated to 30C were acclimated for longer than other treatments. The endpoint used was "the point at which movement could no longer be stimulated, even by prodding"
notes_es: Data digitised from figure. The variability presented in the figure was 2*SE so we divided by two the SD obtained from metaDigitise.

citation: Floyd, Robert B. "Ontogenetic change in the temperature tolerance of larval Bufo marinus (Anura: Bufonidae)." Comparative Biochemistry and Physiology Part A: Physiology 75, no. 2 (1983): 267-271.
minor_concerns: Treatments were acclimated for different durations.
notes_moderators: Data for animals at the Gosner stage 40. Bufo marinus was changed to "Rhinella marina" because the species name changed. The species was considered "aquatic" because they manipulated the water temperature. Geographical coordinates were not taken because the location was approximate ("campus of Griffith University, Brisbane, Australia"). Griffith University has now expanded greatly. Season was taken to be "summer" as animals were collected in February in Australia. "mobility" was taken as "mobile" because the incubation spanned both immobile and mobile life stages. All embryos developed at 30C and were then allocated to different treatments, meaning that animals acclimated to 30C were acclimated for longer than other treatments. The endpoint used was "the point at which movement could no longer be stimulated, even by prodding"
notes_es: Data digitised from figure. The variability presented in the figure was 2*SE so we divided by two the SD obtained from metaDigitise.

note_ID: Treatments were re-used in stepwise comparisons.

title: Out of the frying pan into the airemersion behaviour and evaporative heat loss in an amphibious mangrove fish (Kryptolebias marmoratus)
citation: Gibson, Daniel J., Emma VA Sylvester, Andy J. Turko, Glenn J. Tattersall, and Patricia A. Wright. "Out of the frying pan into the airemersion behaviour and evaporative heat loss in an amphibious mangrove fish (Kryptolebias marmoratus)." Biology letters 11, no. 10 (2015): 20150689.
minor_concerns: Treatments were acclimated for different durations.
notes_moderators: Body mass was calculated from the raw data as the mean between the two treatments compared. The incubation_temp_independent was taken as "no" because animals in one experimental group were acclimated for longer (i.e., animals were acclimated at 25 or 30C, and then re-acclimated to 25C). The endpoint was the "emersion threshold temperature"

title: Variation in developmental temperature alters adulthood plasticity of thermal tolerance in Tigriopus californicus
citation: Healy, Timothy M., Antonia K. Bock, and Ronald S. Burton. "Variation in developmental temperature alters adulthood plasticity of thermal tolerance in Tigriopus californicus." Journal of Experimental Biology 222, no. 22 (2019).
minor_concerns: Treatments were acclimated for different durations.
notes_moderators: Data for the Bird Rock (BR) population acclimated to 20C as adults. Geographical coordinates were taken from Tab S1. The endpoint was "the loss of locomotor performance (i.e. knockdown)". Ramping rate was taken to be 0.1C/min although temperature was ramped at 0.1C/20 seconds from 20 to 32C (which is lower than any of the CTmax recorded).  Treatments were acclimated for different durations (14 days at 20C and 10 days at 25C) to synchronise the developmental stage of the animals. Because animals were developmentally acclimated to 20 or 25C and then re-acclimated to 20 or 25C as adults, the duration of acclimation is also always longer for one of the treatments.
notes_es: Data calculated from the raw data

note_ID: Three populations ("thermally selected", "Nagano" and "Donaldson") were used in this study. The first two were used for CTmax assays, whereas only the thermally selected and Donaldson populations were used for LT50 assays. LOE and death were measured on the same animals, hence the shared cohort_ID.
title: Thermal tolerance of a rainbow trout Oncorhynchus mykiss strain selected by high-temperature breeding
citation: Ineno, Toshinao, Shuji Tsuchida, Mikio Kanda, and Shugo Watabe. "Thermal tolerance of a rainbow trout Oncorhynchus mykiss strain selected by high-temperature breeding." Fisheries Science 71, no. 4 (2005): 767-775.
notes_moderators: Data for the "thermally selected" strain, where parents were exposed to 31-35C for 1-5 min during their life and the survived fish were used for reproduction. Acc_duration was "1 month" so it was taken as 30 days. Age_tested was "6 months" so it was taken as 365/2
notes_es: Data digitised from figure

note_ID: Three populations ("thermally selected", "Nagano" and "Donaldson") were used in this study. The first two were used for CTmax assays, whereas only the thermally selected and Donaldson populations were used for LT50 assays.
title: Thermal tolerance of a rainbow trout Oncorhynchus mykiss strain selected by high-temperature breeding
citation: Ineno, Toshinao, Shuji Tsuchida, Mikio Kanda, and Shugo Watabe. "Thermal tolerance of a rainbow trout Oncorhynchus mykiss strain selected by high-temperature breeding." Fisheries Science 71, no. 4 (2005): 767-775.
major_concerns: Standard error probably under- or over-estimated because the number of animals at each test temperatures was not clearly stated and is used for calculating LT50.
notes_moderators: Data for embryos at the "early segmentation" stage from the "thermally selected" strain, where survival was measured over 360 min. Acc_duration was different between the two incubation treatments so the mean was taken. Different n_test_temp (5 or 7) were used for the two incubation treatments so the mean number of test temperatures was taken. n_animals_per_replicate was taken as 22,800 eggs divided between 2 strains, 2 acclimation temperatures, 3 developmental stages, 7 test temperatures and 8 set times = ~ 34 individuals for the group incubated to 10C; and ~ 48 for the embryos incubated to 14C (only 5 test temperatures). Therefore, we indicated the n_animals_per_replicates to be approximately 41.
notes_es: Data digitised from figure.  Sample sizes were taken as the number of test temperatures * the number of replicate test temperatures. I fitted a logistic regression and used the dose.p() function from 'MASS' to calculate LT50. The standard error is provided instead of SD. Note that some data points from the figures were not taken because they were irrelevant in calculating LT50 (see NA values in Table 1), or calculating comparisons between the two incubation treatments. Therefore, only the LT50 estimations relevant to our study were included here.

notes_moderators: Data for embryos at the "early segmentation" stage from the "thermally selected" strain, where survival was measured over 360 min. Acc_duration was different between the two incubation treatments so the mean was taken. Different n_test_temp (5 or 7) were used for the two incubation treatments so the mean number of test temperatures was taken. n_animals_per_replicate was taken as 22,800 eggs divided between 2 strains, 2 acclimation temperatures, 3 developmental stages, 7 test temperatures and 8 set times = ~ 34 individuals for the group incubated to 10C; and ~ 48 for the embryos incubated to 14C (only 5 test temperatures). Therefore, we indicated the n_animals_per_replicates to be approximately 41.
notes_es: Data digitised from figure.  Sample sizes were taken as the number of test temperatures * the number of replicate test temperatures. I fitted a logistic regression and used the dose.p() function from 'MASS' to calculate LT50. The standard error is provided instead of SD. Note that some data points from the figures were not taken because they were irrelevant in calculating LT50 (see NA values in Table 1), or calculating comparisons between the two incubation treatments. Therefore, only the LT50 estimations relevant to our study were included here.

note_ID: Three populations ("thermally selected", "Nagano" and "Donaldson") were used in this study. The first two were used for CTmax assays, whereas only the thermally selected and Donaldson populations were used for LT50 assays.

title: Adjusting to climate: Acclimation, adaptation and developmental plasticity in physiological traits of a tropical rainforest lizard
citation: Llewelyn, John, Stewart L. Macdonald, Craig Moritz, Felipe Martins, Amberlee Hatcher, and Ben L. Phillips. "Adjusting to climate: Acclimation, adaptation and developmental plasticity in physiological traits of a tropical rainforest lizard." Integrative Zoology 13, no. 4 (2018): 411-427.
notes_moderators: Data for the "HR" population. Year was taken as 2013 although the sampling effort occurred between June 2013 and February 2014. time_common_temp and age_tested were calculated as the age of the animals (1 month = 30 days) + the 2 days that separated the CTmin trial and the CTmax trial (see methods). Embryos were incubated until hatching but the exact acc_duration was not reported.

title: Independent and Interactive Effects of Long-Term Exposure to Hypoxia and Elevated Water Temperature on Behavior and Thermal Tolerance of an Equatorial Cichlid
citation: McDonnell, Laura H., J. E. Reemeyer, and Lauren J. Chapman. "Independent and interactive effects of long-term exposure to hypoxia and elevated water temperature on behavior and thermal tolerance of an equatorial cichlid." Physiological and Biochemical Zoology 92, no. 3 (2019): 253-265.
notes_moderators: Data for fish in the normoxia condition. Reproduction mode was considered as "viviparous" because this species is mouth-breeding and the embryo incubation is experienced through the parent. Coordinates were estimated from Google Earth using the location presented in Fig. 1 of Crispo and Chapman 2010. Season was taken as "summer" because animals were captured in July in Uganda. Age, body mass and body length (standard length) from Tab 1 were averaged between acclimation treatments. Oxygen concentrations were approximated from % of air saturation to mg/L using the equivalence presented in the main text ("1.7-7.7 mg/L, ~18%-90% air saturation)
notes_es: Data digitised from figure.

title: Effects of warming rate, acclimation temperature and ontogeny on the critical thermal maximum of temperate marine fish larvae
citation: Moyano, Marta, Caroline Candebat, Yannick Ruhbaum, Santiago Alvarez-Fernandez, Guy Claireaux, Jose-Luis Zambonino-Infante, and Myron A. Peck. "Effects of warming rate, acclimation temperature and ontogeny on the critical thermal maximum of temperate marine fish larvae." PLoS One 12, no. 7 (2017): e0179928.
minor_concerns: Animals were of a different age when tested.
notes_moderators: Animals in different acclimation treatments were tested at different ages. We only took the comparisons where the age of the animals tested were relatively close (20-14 dph and 45-43 dph) to reduce the age bias. The age and body length were averaged between acclimation treatments. The duration of acclimation was the mean age of the animals minus the 9 days it took for experimenters to reach the acclimation temperatures. Acclimation temperatures and salinities were averaged between treatments.
notes_es: Data calculated from the raw data. Comparisons between certain age groups were not included because judged to the difference in age between acclimation treatments was judged too important.

note_ID: Treatments were re-used in stepwise comparisons.
title: Immediate and Persistent Effects of Temperature on Oxygen Consumption and Thermal Tolerance in Embryos and Larvae of the Baja California Chorus Frog, Pseudacris hypochondriaca
citation: Mueller, Casey A., Julie Bucsky, Lindsey Korito, and Samantha Manzanares. "Immediate and persistent effects of temperature on oxygen consumption and thermal tolerance in embryos and larvae of the Baja California chorus frog, Pseudacris hypochondriaca." Frontiers in physiology 10 (2019): 754.
minor_concerns: Eggs were collected from the wild.
notes_moderators: Data for the animals re-acclimated to 20C. Eggs were collected from the wild so the early embryonic conditions (before Gosner stage 8-9, ~first 24h post fertilization) were not entirely controlled.  Mobility_life_stage_manip was considered "mobile" because incubation spanned both the embryo (immobile) and larval stage (mobile). The season was taken to be "summer" because animals were collected between January and March in California (USA). Year was taken as 2017, although animals were collected in both 2017 and 2018. acc_duration was taken as the average time to 50% hatch between treatments (digitised from Fig2B) minus one (the age of the embryos when collected) + 6 (the median time animals were kept as larvae before being brought to a common temperature). The time_common_temperature was taken as 14 days as a conservative estimate because larvae were acclimated "for a minimum of 2 weeks".

note_ID: NA
title: Importance of experienced thermal history: Effect of acclimation temperatures on the high-temperature tolerance and growth performance of juvenile marbled flounder
citation: Sakurai, Gento, Satoshi Takahashi, Yusei Yoshida, Hiroshi Yoshida, Jun Shoji, and Takeshi Tomiyama. "Importance of experienced thermal history: Effect of acclimation temperatures on the high-temperature tolerance and growth performance of juvenile marbled flounder." Journal of Thermal Biology 97 (2021): 102831.
notes_moderators: Body length was averaged between the treatment groups. Housing_temp was taken as the mean of the range presented (11-15C). Duration of acclimation was slightly different between the test temperatures (13 or 14d) so the average duration of acclimation was taken.
notes_es: Data taken from figure. The data was not digitised because the mortality presented was always either 0 or 1. Sample sizes were taken as the n_test_temp * n_replicates_per_temp. I fitted a logistic regression and used the dose.p() function from 'MASS' to calculate LT50. Unfortunately, the model failed to converge and the SE estimated from the model was very large. Therefore, the mean LT50 was the one presented in the abstract and the standard error was reported as "NA".

title:
The thermal macrophysiology of core and marginal
populations of the aphid Myzus persicae in Europe
citation: Alford, Lucy. "The thermal macrophysiology of core and marginal populations of the aphid Myzus persicae in Europe." PhD diss., University of Birmingham, 2010.
minor_concerns: Treatments were acclimated for different durations
notes_moderators: Data for the Span-1 clones. Exposure through mother conditions (viviparous) for one generation. Geographical coordinates were not taken because too approximate. 20C was the housing temperature for multiple generations, hence why incubation_independent was taken as "no". Endpoint was the "heat movement threshold, the temperature at which movement ceased". Ramping was taken as 0.1C/min although experimenters first used a ramping rate of 0.5C/min until reaching 35C. Because the CTmax of all animals was above 35C, the latest ramping rate was taken.

note_ID: NA
title: Reversibility of developmental heat and cold plasticity is asymmetric and has long-lasting consequences for adult thermal tolerance
citation: Slotsbo, Stine, Mads F. Schou, Torsten N. Kristensen, Volker Loeschcke, and Jesper G. Sørensen. "Reversibility of developmental heat and cold plasticity is asymmetric and has long-lasting consequences for adult thermal tolerance." Journal of Experimental Biology 219, no. 17 (2016): 2726-2732.
minor_concerns: Treatments were acclimated for different durations. Medians were presented
notes_moderators: Data for adults acclimated to 15C for 3 hours. mobility_life_stage_manip was taken as "immobile" because most of the life stages acclimated were immobile (embryos and pupae). Geographical coordinates were taken from Schou et al. 2014 (see citation in the paper) and elevant was inferred using https://latlongdata.com/elevation/. Season was taken as "fall" because animals were originally captured in October in Denmark. Endpoint was "the temperature at which all capacity for movement ceased". acc_duration not reported because the development time was not reported.  Animals who were first incubated at 15C were acclimated for longer than the animals incubated to 25C; hence why "incubation_independent" was taken as "no".
notes_es: Data digitised from figure. The data presented were medians and not means. Raw data was presented in the supplement, but in PDF format (unusable).

title: Reversibility of developmental heat and cold plasticity is asymmetric and has long-lasting consequences for adult thermal tolerance

minor_concerns: Treatments were acclimated for different durations. Medians were presented

title: Temperature Responses of Young Schlegel's Black Rockfish Sebastes schlegeli
citation: Tsuchida, Shuji, and Takumi Setoguma. "Temperature responses of young Schlegel's black rockfish Sebastes schlegeli." Nippon Suisan Gakkaishi 63, no. 3 (1997): 317-325.
major_concerns: The CTmax was estimated from death times at different temperatures (thermal tolerance landscapes).\
notes_moderators: Study was published in Japanese. deepl.com/translator was used to translate the text to English. N_test_temp was taken as the number of temperatures used to infer the thermal death time curves.
notes_es: Time to death at different temperatures taken from Table 2. Data calculated by fitting a linear regression of log10(time to death) against the test temperatures according to Jorgensen et al. 2018,2021 and Rezende et al. 2014. The CTmax was estimated as the temperatures animals cannot withstand for longer than 60 minutes. The sample size was taken as the n_test_temp * n_replicates_per_temp. The LT50 was technically possible to calculate but the standard error calculated from logistic regressions were so large that the data is probably not accurate.

title: Interspecific differences, plastic, and evolutionary responses to a heat wave in three co-occurring Daphnia species
citation: Vanvelk, Héléne, Lynn Govaert, Edwin M. Van den Berg, Kristien I. Brans, and Luc De Meester. "Interspecific differences, plastic, and evolutionary responses to a heat wave in three co?occurring Daphnia species." Limnology and Oceanography 66, no. 4 (2021): 1201-1220.
minor_concerns: Treatments were acclimated for different durations.
notes_moderators: Elevation estimated using https://latlongdata.com/elevation/. Season was taken as "spring" because animals were collected in April-May in Belgium. Animals acclimated to 20C were acclimated for longer than animals acclimated to 26C because the former was the housing_temp. CTmax was measured "upon reaching sexual maturity". Endpoint was the "loss of motor function", which was considered analogous to LRR. Body length was digitised from figure 2B. Age at maturity (acc_duration) was digitised from figure 2E.
notes_es: Data digitised from figure.

title: Influence of a dynamic rearing environment on development of metabolic phenotypes in age-0 Lake Sturgeon, Acipenser fulvescens
citation: Yoon, Gwangseok R., David Deslauriers, and W. Gary Anderson. "Influence of a dynamic rearing environment on development of metabolic phenotypes in age-0 Lake Sturgeon, Acipenser fulvescens." Conservation physiology 7, no. 1 (2019): coz055.
minor_concerns: The temperatures of acclimation were not the exact values; but the difference between the two temperatures was correct.
notes_moderators: Data with substrate. Season was taken to be "spring" because animals were captured in May in Canada. Acc_duration was the age of the animals tested minus the age at which they were put in treatment (32 dph). Acclimation temperatures were highly fluctuating so the temperatures reported for acc_temp_low and acc_temp_high are very approximate. However, the difference in temperature between these treatments is accurate.
notes_es: Data digitised from figure. Sample size was unclear but Table S3 indicate that comparisons between CTmax at 55dph and 272 dph have a df of 15. Therefore, half of the sample size was allocated to 7 in each treatment.

title: The effects of embryonic incubation temperature on subsequent development, growth, and thermal tolerance through early ontogeny of white sturgeon
citation: Cheung, Katherine. "The effects of embryonic incubation temperature on subsequent development, growth, and thermal tolerance through early ontogeny of white sturgeon." PhD diss., University of British Columbia, 2019.
minor_concerns: Treatments were acclimated for different durations.
notes_moderators: Data for animals originating from "female 2522". Acc_temp_var and ramping were taken as the means of the ranges presented. Endpoint was the "lack of motor response following 3 consecutive tail prods". Animals incubated at 15C were acclimated for longer because 15C was the common temperature at which animals were brought to; hence why "incubation_independent" was taken as "no". Geographical coordinates were not taken because too approximate ("Nechako River"). Season was taken as "spring" because animals were collected in May in Canada. acc_duration was taken as the mean number of days to 50% hatch between treatments. Body mass and body length were digitised from figure 2.7, 2.8 and 2.9 and were averaged between treatments.
notes_es: Data digitised from figure.

notes_moderators: Data for animals originating from "female 5903". Acc_temp_var and ramping were taken as the means of the ranges presented. Endpoint was the "lack of motor response following 3 consecutive tail prods". Animals incubated at 15C were acclimated for longer because 15C was the common temperature at which animals were brought to; hence why "incubation_independent" was taken as "no". Geographical coordinates were not taken because too approximate ("Nechako River"). Season was taken as "spring" because animals were collected in May in Canada. acc_duration was taken as the mean number of days to 50% hatch between treatments. Body mass and body length were digitised from figure 2.7, 2.8 and 2.9 and were averaged between treatments.

title: Effect of latitude and acclimation on the lethal temperatures of the peach-potato aphid Myzus persicae
citation: Alford, Lucy, Tim M. Blackburn, and Jeffrey S. Bale. "Effect of latitude and acclimation on the lethal temperatures of the peach?potato aphid Myzus persicae." Agricultural and Forest Entomology 14, no. 1 (2012): 69-79.
minor_concerns: Treatments were acclimated for different durations
major_concerns: Very short set_time at the test temperatures.
notes_moderators: Data for the Span-1 clones. Exposure through mother conditions (viviparous) for one generation. Geographical coordinates were not taken because too approximate. 20C was the housing temperature for multiple generations, hence why incubation_independent was taken as "no". Animals were brought to the test temperatures at a rate of 0.5C/min, maintained at the test temperature for 10 seconds, and brought back to the acclimation temperature. The survival was recorded 72h after the exposure to the test temperatures.
notes_es: Data taken from table. Sample sizes were taken as the number of test temperatures * the number of replicate test temperatures. Confidence intervals were converted to SD by dividing the confidence intervals by 1.96. SE is reported instead of SD.

note_ID: NA
title: Thermal acclimation in a complex life cycle: The effects of larval and adult thermal conditions on metabolic rate and heat resistance in Culex pipiens (Diptera: Culicidae)
citation: Gray, Emilie M. "Thermal acclimation in a complex life cycle: the effects of larval and adult thermal conditions on metabolic rate and heat resistance in Culex pipiens (Diptera: Culicidae)." Journal of insect physiology 59, no. 10 (2013): 1001-1007.
minor_concerns: Eggs were collected from the wild. Treatments were acclimation for different durations.
notes_moderators: Season was taken to be "summer" because animals were collected between mid June and mid September in Colorado (USA). Eggs were collected from the wild so a portion of the development occurred outside controlled conditions. Animals incubated to 18C were acclimated for 3-4 days longer than animals incubated at 26C; and all animals were then re-incubated at 18C at the adult stage. Humidity was taken as the mean of the range presented (60-70%). acc_duration was taken as 12 days because authors indicate that "time between first exposure to the experimental temperature and pupation was at least 12 days". Age was taken as the mean of the range presented (4-5 days). Body mass (dry mass) was calculated as the mean dry mass of both treatments from the raw data. Endpoint was "the final 10s of spiracular activity displayed by the insect".
notes_es: Data calculated from the raw data (obtained from the author).

title: Thermal Biology of the New Zealand Sea Urchin Evechinus chloroticus
citation: Delorme Juri, Natali. "Thermal biology of the New Zealand sea urchin Evechinus chloroticus." PhD diss., ResearchSpace@ Auckland, 2017.
minor_concerns: Animals in each acclimation treatment were sampled at different times from the field and parents experienced different conditions.
notes_moderators: Data for gastrula. acc_duration not reported. Animals acclimated to 18C were not collected during the same event as animals acclimated to 21 or 24C, and parents in the 18C acclimation treatment were acclimated to 18C for 90 days. We still included this data but did not include the year/season the animals were sampled because of the heterogeneity in sampling events. Mobility was taken as "immobile" because larval stages of echinoderms have a limited motility.
notes_es: Data digitised from figure. Sample sizes were taken as the number of test temperatures * the number of replicate test temperatures. Confidence intervals were divided by 1.96 to calculate standard error. SE is reported instead of SD.

title: Thermal tolerance and compatibility zones as a tool to establish the optimum culture condition of the halibut Paralichthys californicus (Ayres, 1859)
citation: Esquer Mendez, José L., Mónica Hernández Rodríguez, and Luis F. Bückle Ramirez. "Thermal tolerance and compatibility zones as a tool to establish the optimum culture condition of the halibut Paralichthys californicus (Ayres, 1859)." Aquaculture Research 41, no. 7 (2010): 1015-1021.
major_concerns: SE was taken instead of the SD reported.
notes_moderators: I was unclear to us how the LT50 data was presented so we contacted the authors of the study and they indicated that "You can check table 2, for each acclimation temperature are the thermal baths to which the fish were exposed. In this table is the mean and standard deviation for the observed data, as well as the LT50 value. E.g. AT 15 °C,  LT50 = 29.9 ± 0.06; AT 18 °C, LT50 = 30.9 ± 0.05; AT 20°C, LT50 = 30.9  ± 0.08; AT 24 °C, LT50 = 30.9 ± 0.06.". acc_temp_var, oxygen, body_length, and body_mass were taken as the mean of the two treatments compared. set_time was not reported.
notes_es: Data obtained from the authors of the original study and presented in table 2. Although authors report "standard deviations", these values seem closer to standard errors (and estimations from linear regressions usually return standard errors) so we considered the sd_low and sd_high as SE instead of SD. Sample sizes were taken as the number of test temperatures * the number of replicate test temperatures.

title: Upper thermal tolerances of early life stages of freshwater mussels
journal: Journal of the North American Benthological Society
citation: Pandolfo, Tamara J., W. Gregory Cope, Consuelo Arellano, Robert B. Bringolf, M. Christopher Barnhart, and Edward Hammer. "Upper thermal tolerances of early life stages of freshwater mussels." Journal of the North American Benthological Society 29, no. 3 (2010): 959-969.
notes_moderators: Mobility was taken as "immobile" because the mobility of mussels is quite limited. Housing_temp was averaged because two different temperatures were reported (17 and 22C). Age_tested was taken as the mean of the range presented (3 to 8 weeks).
notes_es: Data taken from table. Sample sizes were taken as the number of test temperatures * the number of replicate test temperatures. Confidence intervals were converted to SD by dividing the confidence intervals by 1.96. SE is reported instead of SD. We did not include data on glochidia because the animals were only acclimated for 2 hours, which did not fit our inclusion criteria (>24 hour acclimation).

title: Upper and Lower Temperature Tolerance Limits for Juvenile Red Drums from Texas and South Carolina
citation: Procarione, Lynne S., and Tim L. King. "Upper and lower temperature tolerance limits for juvenile red drums from Texas and South Carolina." Journal of Aquatic Animal Health 5, no. 3 (1993): 208-212.
minor_concerns: Treatments were acclimated for different durations
notes_moderators: Data for the Texas red drum. 20C was the housing_temp so animals acclimated to 20C were acclimated for longer than the other groups, hence why incubation_indedependent was taken as "no". Acc_temp_var was averaged between treatments (see table 1). Acc_duration was taken as the mean of the range presented (19-26 days). age_tested was taken as the age of the fish when they started the first acclimation (30d) + the 4 months before the start of the experiments + the 3 days of pre-acclimatiom + 7 days of adjustment period + 19-26 days of acclimation.
notes_es: Data taken from table. Sample sizes were taken as the number of test temperatures * the number of replicate test temperatures. Confidence intervals were converted to SD by dividing the confidence intervals by 1.96. SE is reported instead of SD.

note_ID: "Winter" and "Summer" eggs were considered separate populations and families.
title: Differential impacts of ocean acidification and warming on winter and summer progeny of a coastal squid (Loligo vulgaris)
citation: Rosa, Rui, Katja Trübenbach, Marta S. Pimentel, Joana Boavida-Portugal, Filipa Faleiro, Miguel Baptista, Gisela Dionísio, Ricardo Calado, Hans O. Pörtner, and Tiago Repolho. "Differential impacts of ocean acidification and warming on winter and summer progeny of a coastal squid (Loligo vulgaris)." Journal of Experimental Biology 217, no. 4 (2014): 518-525.
minor_concerns: Eggs were collected from the wild.
notes_moderators: Data for late embryos from eggs collected in Winter. The LT50 was measured while the temperature was increased gradually; and the percentage of living animals at each temperature was determined. This is an hybrid between CTmax and LT50, hence why a ramping rate was assigned but not n_test_temp. Set_time was taken as 30 min because temperatures was increased every 30 min and the survival of the animals was assessed before each ramp. salinity, pH, acc_temp_var and acclimation temperatures were averaged between treatments (see table S3 for original values). n_test_temp was taken as 20 because temperature was increased at a rate of 1C/30min from the temperature of acclimation until all animals died and 20 * 3 animals were used for each treatment. Assuming a maximum temperature reached of 39C (which seems consistent with LT100 values displayed in Fig. 5), we can asssume n_test_temp to be approximatively 20.
notes_es: Data digitised from figure. Sample sizes were taken as the number of test temperatures * the number of replicate test temperatures. Note that n_test_temp was estimated and is not exact. Although authors report "standard deviations", these values seem closer to standard errors (and estimations from linear regressions usually return standard errors) so we considered the sd_low and sd_high as SE instead of SD.

citation: Sasmita, Hadian Iman, Wu-Chun Tu, Lee-Jin Bong, and Kok-Boon Neoh. minor_concerns: Treatments were acclimated for different durations.
notes_moderators: Data for animals fed with the "Khan's" diet. Was considered "terrestrial" because the life stage tested is terrestrial. The authors were contacted and indicated that animals were re-acclimated to the laboratory temperature after pupation. The age_tested and time_common_temp were taken as the mean of the range presented (3-5 days). Body length (cephalotorax length) was digitised from figure 3. Animals acclimated to 25C were acclimated for longer than the other experimental group because this was the housing_temperature and the common_temp.
notes_es: Data taken from table. Sample sizes were taken as the number of test temperatures * the number of replicate test temperatures. Confidence intervals were converted to SD by dividing the confidence intervals by 1.96. SE is reported instead of SD.

title: Thermal tolerance and locomotor activity of blue swimmer crab Portunus pelagicus instar reared at different temperatures
citation: Azra, Mohamad N., Jiann-Chu Chen, Mhd Ikhwanuddin, and Ambok Bolong Abol-Munafi. "Thermal tolerance and locomotor activity of blue swimmer crab Portunus pelagicus instar reared at different temperatures." Journal of thermal biology 74 (2018): 234-240.
notes_moderators: age_tested was taken as the age of the animals when they reached the first instar (4 days) + the time to reach the eighth instar (120 days) + the duration of acclimation (3 weeks). Housing_temp, salinity, and pH were takern as the mean of the ranges presented.
notes_es: Data digitised from figure. Sample sizes were taken as 20 because authors indicate that "five crabs were place in five individual containers" and "each thermal tolerance assay was repeated four to five times, and each crab was used only once in the tests". Note that the standard deviation was not presented and hence, was presented as "NA". Note that the x axis on the figure was incorrect and we took the x values to be the acclimation temperatures in the text, in order.

notes_moderators: age_tested was taken as the age of the animals when they reached the first instar (4 days) + the time to reach the eighth instar (120 days) + the duration of acclimation (3 weeks). Housing_temp, salinity, and pH were takern as the mean of the ranges presented. Animals acclimated to 28C were acclimated for longer because it was the housing_temp.
notes_es: Data digitised from figure. Sample sizes were taken as 20 because authors indicate that "five crabs were place in five individual containers" and "each thermal tolerance assay was repeated four to five times, and each crab was used only once in the tests". Note that the standard deviation was not presented and hence, was presented as "NA". Note that the x axis on the figure was incorrect and we took the x values to be the acclimation temperatures in the text, in order.

notes_es: Data taken from table. I fitted a logistic regression and use the dose.p() function from 'MASS' to calculate LT50. title: Ocean warming and acidification pose synergistic limits to the thermal niche of an economically important echinoderm
citation: Manríquez, Patricio H., Claudio P. González, Katherina Brokordt, Luis Pereira, Rodrigo Torres, María E. Lattuca, Daniel A. Fernández et al. "Ocean warming and acidification pose synergistic limits to the thermal niche of an economically important echinoderm." Science of The Total Environment 693 (2019): 133469.
notes_moderators: Data for animals exposed to current pCO2 levels. Collective parent group collected from wild at a subtidal location nearby to reported coordinates, but study organisms reared in lab. No specific mention of families. Body mass was the wet mass. Endpoint was the "failure to self-right within 20 min", which was taken as akin to the LRR. body_mass, body_length, acc_temp_var, ramping, salinity and pH were averaged between the treatments compared.
notes_es: Data taken from table. SE was converted to SD.

title: Critical and Chronic Thermal Maxima of Northern and Florida Largemouth Bass and Their Reciprocal F1 and F2 Hybrids
journal: Transactions of the American Fisheries Society
citation: Fields, Robert, Shirley S. Lowe, Christine Kaminski, Gregory S. Whitt, and David P. Philipp. "Critical and chronic thermal maxima of northern and Florida largemouth bass and their reciprocal F1 and F2 hybrids." Transactions of the American Fisheries Society 116, no. 6 (1987): 856-863.
notes_moderators: Data for F1 animals originating from parents taken from Bone Lake, Wisconsin (northern, N). Coordinates approximated from Google Maps using the name of the lakes provided. Fish were housed in an outdoor pond facility and the housing_temp was taken as 10C because authors mention that the temperatures were 10-12C. Body length was taken as the mean of the range provided (50-60) and was the body length before the acclimation period. Authors indicate that "Fish used at final acclimation temperatures of 8 and 16C were collected at a field temperature of 6C whereas the field collection temperature was 20C for fish used at final acclimation temperatures of 24 and 32C" but it is unclear what "field" temperatures the authors mention.

minor_concerns: Body mass and body length before acclimation.
notes_moderators: Body_mass and body_length were the morphology before the acclimation period of 20 days. Age_tested was taken as the age of the animals when they arrived in the lab (6 weeks) + the acc_duration.
notes_es: Data taken from the main text (results section).

note_ID: Nine populations were used in this study. Treatments were re-used in stepwise comparisons. The same individuals were tested at 90dph and when they reached ~1g of body mass, hence the shared cohort_IDs.
title: Optimum and maximum temperatures of sockeye salmon (Oncorhynchus nerka) populations hatched at different temperatures
citation: Chen, Z., K. Anttila, J. Wu, C. K. Whitney, S. G. Hinch, and A. P. Farrell. "Optimum and maximum temperatures of sockeye salmon (Oncorhynchus nerka) populations hatched at different temperatures." Canadian Journal of Zoology 91, no. 5 (2013): 265-274.
notes_moderators: Data for the "Harrison" population. Coordinates were approximated from Google Maps based on Fig. 1. Ramping was taken as 0.1C/min because this was the latest ramping rate used before reaching CTmax; but note that authors used 0.3C/min until reaching 20C. Common_temp was taken as the mean of the range presented (5-7C)
notes_es: Data taken from table. Sample size was taken as the mean of the range presented (20-24), except for fish from the Harrison population incubated at 16C (n=13). SE was converted to SD.

title: Thermal tolerance and phenotypic plasticity in juvenile Hippocampus erectus Perry, 1810: Effect of acute and chronic exposure to contrasting temperatures
journal: Journal of Experimental Marine Biology and Ecology
citation: Mascaró, M., M. Amaral-Ruiz, I. Huipe-Zamora, G. Martínez-Moreno, N. Simoes, and C. Rosas. "Thermal tolerance and phenotypic plasticity in juvenile Hippocampus erectus Perry, 1810: effect of acute and chronic exposure to contrasting temperatures." Journal of experimental marine biology and ecology 483 (2016): 112-119.
notes_moderators: Reproduction mode was considered as "viviparous" because males carry eggs and the embryo incubation is experienced through the parent. endpoint was considered to be the "stress" phase (see table 2 for details). Seahorses were collected from two males, not clear whether treatments contained a mix of juvenile seahorses from both males or whether they remained in separate treatments. The age of testing was determined from 4.5 months of standard protocol, followed by 4 days of preparation to acclimation and 30 days of acclimation. Body mass was taken as the mean progeny mass from both males.
notes_es: Data taken from table.

minor_concerns: Treatments were acclimated for different durations.

title: Thyroid hormone levels and temperature during development alter thermal tolerance and energetics of Xenopus laevis larvae
citation: Ruthsatz, Katharina, Kathrin H. Dausmann, Myron A. Peck, Claudia Drees, Nikita M. Sabatino, Laura I. Becker, Janica Reese, Lisa Hartmann, and Julian Glos. "Thyroid hormone levels and temperature during development alter thermal tolerance and energetics of Xenopus laevis larvae." Conservation physiology 6, no. 1 (2018): coy059.
notes_moderators: This study manipulated levels of the thyroid hormone as well as the acclimation temperature, and effect sizes were only generated from the control treatment with no hormone manipulation. Body mass was taken as the average body mass at the onset of metamorphosis across between treatments (see Tab A1 for original values). The species was considered "aquatic" because the life stage tested is aquatic. Acc_temp_var was averaged between treatments.

title: Upper Lethal Temperatures for Larval Salmonids
citation: Bishai, H. M. "Upper lethal temperatures for larval salmonids." ICES Journal of Marine Science 25, no. 2 (1960): 129-133.
minor_concerns: Treatments were acclimated for different durations.
major_concerns: The CTmax was estimated from death times at different temperatures (thermal tolerance landscapes).
notes_moderators: Data for salmon. Animals acclimated to 5.5C were acclimated for longer because it was the housing_temp.
notes_es: Time to death at different temperatures taken from Table 2. Data calculated by fitting a linear regression of log10(time to 50% mortality) against the test temperatures according to Jorgensen et al. 2018,2021 and Rezende et al. 2014. The CTmax was estimated as the temperatures animals cannot withstand for longer than 60 minutes. The sample size was taken as the n_test_temp * n_replicates_per_temp. The LT50 was technically possible to calculate but the standard error calculated from logistic regressions would be so large that the data is probably not accurate.

title: Thermal tolerance of juvenile Pacific salmon and steelhead trout in relation to supersaturation of nitrogen gas
citation: Ebel, Wesley J., Earl M. Dawley, and Bruce H. Monk. "Thermal tolerance of juvenile Pacific salmon and steelhead trout in relation to supersaturation of nitrogen gas." Fishery Bulletin 69 (1971): 833-843.
minor_concerns: Treatments were acclimated for different durations.

notes_moderators: Data for animals who experienced normal nitrogen saturation in acclimation tanks, and supersaturation (125-130%) in test tanks. acc_duration was taken as the time at the final acclimation temperature (see tab 1) and averaged between treatments. Body mass and body length were averaged between treatments. Nitrogen supersaturation happens in natural conditions so this data was deemed relevant.
notes_es: Time to death at different temperatures taken from tables. Data calculated by fitting a linear regression of log10(time to 50% mortality) against the test temperatures according to Jorgensen et al. 2018,2021 and Rezende et al. 2014. major_concerns: The CTmax was estimated from death times at different temperatures (thermal tolerance landscapes).
notes_moderators: Data for animals who experienced nitrogen supersaturation (125-130%) in both acclimation and test tanks. acc_duration was taken as the time at the final acclimation temperature (see tab 1) and averaged between treatments. N_test_temp was taken as the median number of test temperatures. n_replicates_per_temp was taken as "2" because authors indicate that "all tests were then repeated (most tests were duplicated, some were done three times)". Body mass and body length were averaged between treatments. Nitrogen supersaturation happens in natural conditions so this data was deemed relevant.
notes_es: Time to death at different temperatures taken from tables. Data calculated by fitting a linear regression of log10(time to 50% mortality) against the test temperatures according to Jorgensen et al. 2018,2021 and Rezende et al. 2014. The CTmax was estimated as the temperatures animals cannot withstand for longer than 60 minutes. The sample size was taken as the n_test_temp * n_replicates_per_temp.
